metadata.name: Overgrowth X8 #45
metadata.description:
Overgrowth was an experiment in mixed brushes, and random walks, to create complex scribble landscapes. Overgrowth X8 takes the concept a number of steps forward.

The first change is that there are 8 brush heads rather than 1. The starting location of these brush heads have been curated into 6 sets.

a) Four Corners - 2 brush heads emanating from each corner,
b) All Together Now - All brush heads starting at the same low central location,
c) Great Monument (sometimes),
d) Upon this Slope, these structures are built,
e) Heaven and Earth - 4 brush heads at the top and 4 at the bottom, sometimes they meet,
f) Random Landscaper - All brush heads randomly placed in the lower part of the canvas.

Each brushes white ellipses are now a randomised shade of very light grey. This gives slightly more depth.

As the brushes usually do not randomly fill the whole canvas, there is a background that has been built to be consistent with the drawing, rather than just using a solid color or mono light bands.

White and black stroke sizes have been adapted to give a slightly wider range of effects.

Press s to save a 2400x2400 jpg.

Please note that the progressive rendering may not work on mobile and may be slow on some browsers.

Created with p5.js. This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: a fleeting moment #157
metadata.description:
Abstract expressionism always has been, and always will be, my first love. With this piece, the initial premise was "can I write a bit of code that will render images in the style that I actually paint in real life?" 

It took several full days of poking and prodding, and I departed from the original mission once I had what I was looking for, but in general, I think I succeeded. My wife was looking over my shoulder at one point, and thought I was looking at a scan of one of my actual paintings, which sounds like success to me. 

Created with love in p5.js

metadata.name: In Due Time #98
metadata.description:
“In Due Time” is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht’s mastery of line and Vittoria’s notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria’s poem for the collection:

“In Due Time”
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

Digits “1” through “9” to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: September #348
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
---------------

metadata.name: Leeward #16
metadata.description:
At a certain point in time it might look like you live on the leeward side of life. Just keep in mind that there is always a windward side on the other end of that mountain you need to climb.

A lesson of perspective.

This feeling was the main inspiration and driving factor of this piece. And I hope it can convey an amount of those emotions to you through this art piece. :)


- - - - - - - - - - - - - -


I - info about your mint (features, descriptions)
E - export menu where you can export for all sorts of use cases in any resolution you'd like.
Space - save a simple screenshot image of the canvas


- - - - - - - - - - - - - -


Made with love by Wouter Missler with p5.js

metadata.name: Sugar & Splice #4
metadata.description:
'Sugar & Splice'

Vibrant somethings, full of flavor, dancing within conjoined boundaries.

Controls:
s: Saves an image of the canvas with the current settings
1-6: Scales the canvas size, from 1 (default, 2048px x 2792px) to 6 (12288px x  16752px)
g: Toggles grain texture
t: Toggles background transparency
f: Toggles fit to screen (layout and other factors will change based on the new size, but overall style, colors, etc will remain the same)
p: Shortcut for large print settings: disables the grain texture and scales the canvas to the largest setting
b: Toggles b-side

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #393
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.
